{{other uses}}

A '''"self-made man"''' (later expanded to include "self-made women") is a classic phrase first coined on February 2, 1832 by United States senator [[Henry Clay]] who referred to the self-made man in the United States senate, to describe individuals in the manufacturing sector whose success lay within the individuals themselves, not with outside conditions. [[Benjamin Franklin]], one of the [[Founding Fathers of the United States]], has been described as the greatest exemplar of the self-made man. Inspired by Franklin's autobiography, [[Frederick Douglass]] developed the concept of the self-made man in a [[Self-Made Men|series of lectures]] that spanned decades starting in 1859. Originally, the term referred to an individual who arises from a poor or otherwise [[disadvantaged]] background to eminence in financial, political or other areas by nurturing qualities, such as perseverance and hard work, as opposed to achieving these goals through [[Inheritance|inherited fortune]], family connections, or other privileges. By the mid-1950s, success in the United States generally implied "business success".

According to the 2017 "World Ultra Wealth Report" by research company [[Wealth-X]], self-made individuals, mainly men, have "largely driven" global "wealth creation" from 1997 through 2017. The report noted that while there are an increasing number of women who are designated as high net worth, most inherited their wealth and only a small percentage sourced their wealth as self-made.

In the intellectual and [[cultural history of the United States]], the idea of the self-made man as an archetype or cultural ideal has been criticized by some as being a [[myth]] or a [[cult]].

==Origins==
[[File:Benjamin Franklin by Joseph Duplessis 1778.jpg|left|thumb|Benjamin Franklin. c. 1785. Oil by Duplessis]]Benjamin Franklin, one of the [[Founding Fathers of the United States]], has been described as "undoubtedly the original self-made man."<ref name="Slate_2014">{{cite news|last=Swansburg|first=John|title=The Self-Made Man: The story of America’s most pliable, pernicious, irrepressible myth |url=http://www.slate.com/articles/news_and_politics/history/2014/09/the_self_made_man_history_of_a_myth_from_ben_franklin_to_andrew_carnegie.html|work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]|date=September 29, 2014 |access-date=November 12, 2017}}</ref> and the greatest exemplar of the "self-made man".<ref name="Pine_1916_BFB_HR_GP"/> Both the [[American Dream]] and the self-made man concepts are inextricably linked and are rooted in American history. Franklin's autobiography was described by the editor of the 1916 edition, as the "most remarkable of all the remarkable histories of our self-made men".<ref name="Pine_1916_BFB_HR_GP"/> His autobiography, which was dedicated to his son [[William Franklin]], with the first chapter based on a 1771 letter to William,<ref name="Franklin_HarvardClassics">{{Citation| title = Benjamin Franklin, his autobiography| last = Franklin | first = Benjamin| publisher = P.F. Collier & Son | location = New York | series = The Harvard classics. 1909–14 | via = bartleby.com | url = http://www.bartleby.com/1/1/6.html | access-date = 5 July 2006}}</ref> was used as illustrative of the journey of the self-made man in the eighteenth century in [[Colonial United States]]. Franklin's introduced the archetypal self-made man through his own life story in which in spite of all odds he overcame his low and humble origins and inherited social position—his father was candle-maker—to re-invent himself through self-improvement based on a set of strong moral values such as "industry, economy, and perseverance"<ref name="Pine_1916_BFB_HR_GP"/>{{rp|143}} thereby attaining "eminence" in the classic rags to riches narrative. Franklin's maxims as published in his ''Autobiography'' provide others, specifically his own son, with strategies for attaining status in the United States, described as a "land of unequaled opportunity" in the last quarter of the 18th century.<ref name="Franklin_HarvardClassics"/><ref name="Pine_1916_BFB_HR_GP"/>{{rp|143}}

In his 1954 book entitled ''The Self-Made Man in America: The Myth of Rags to Riches'', Irvin G. Wyllie described how on February 2, 1832 [[Henry Clay]] had "coined the phrase 'self-made men'" during his speech to the United States Senate.<ref name="1955_review_Wyllie">{{cite journal |title=Review of "The Self-Made Man in America: The Myth of Rags to Riches" (1954) |first=John William |last=Ward |journal=Journal of American History  |volume=42 |number=2 |date=September 1, 1955 |doi= 10.2307/1897672 |url=https://academic.oup.com/jah/article-abstract/42/2/344/695032?redirectedFrom=fulltext |quote="Clay used the classic phrase to describe the autonomy of our manufacturers ... in behalf of a paternalistic tariff and the irony has persisted throughout the history of the idea of self-help. The essential doctrine behind the self-made man is that success lies within the person himself and not with outside conditions. Wyllie investigated intellectual history, "not the history of a great abstraction but the saga of an idea that had power among the people."}}The Mississippi Valley Historical Review</ref>{{rp|344–345}}<ref name="Wylie_selfmademan_1954">{{cite book |title=The Self-Made Man in America: The Myth of Rags to Riches |first= Irvin G. |last=Wyllie |location=New Brunswick |publisher= Rutgers University Press |year=1954 |pages=210}}</ref><ref name="Wylie_selfmademan_1966">{{cite book |title=The Self-Made Man in America: The Myth of Rags to Riches |first= Irvin G. |last=Wyllie |publisher= Free Press |year=1966}}</ref> Clay used the classic phrase to describe the "autonomy of our manufacturers ... in behalf of a paternalistic tariff" and the "irony has persisted throughout the history of the idea of self-help".<ref name="Wylie_selfmademan_1954"/><ref>{{cite speech |title=The American System |date=February 2, 1832 |first=Henry |last=Clay |editor-first=Wendy |editor-last=Wolfe |volume=3 |series=The Senate (1789–1989) Classic Speeches (1830–1993) Bicentennial Edition |event=United States Senate |location=Washington, D.C. |url=https://www.senate.gov/artandhistory/history/resources/pdf/AmericanSystem.pdf |format=PDF |access-date=November 14, 2017 |quote=..."charge brought against the manufacturing system, as favoring the growth of aristocracy. If it were true, would gentlemen prefer ·supporting foreign accumulations of wealth, by that description of industry, rather than their own country? But is it correct? The joint stock companies of the North, as I understand them, are nothing more than associations, sometimes of hundreds, by means of which the small earnings of many are brought into a common stock; and the associates, obtaining corporate privileges, are enabled to prosecute, under one superintending head, their business to better advantage. Nothing can be more essentially democratic, or better devised to counterpoise the influence of individual wealth. In Kentucky, almost every manufactory known to me is in the hands of enterprising self-made men, who have acquired whatever wealth they possess by patient and diligent labor. Comparisons are odious, and, but in defence, would not be made by me. But is there more tendency to aristocracy in a manufactory, supporting hundreds of freemen, or in a cotton plantation, with its not less numerous slaves, sustaining, perhaps, only two white families-that of the master and the overseer?}}</ref>{{rp|100}}

The essential doctrine behind the self-made man is that success lies within the person himself and not with outside conditions. Wyllie investigated intellectual history, "not the history of a great abstraction but the saga of an idea that had power among the people." To Wyllie, success in the United States by the mid-1950s, generally implied "business success."<ref name="Wylie_selfmademan_1954"/><ref name="1955_review_Wyllie"/>

Franklin and Frederick Douglass,<ref>{{cite book |first=Frederick |last=Douglass |title=[[Narrative of the Life of Frederick Douglass, an American Slave]] |year=1845}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |first=Frederick |last=Douglass |title=[[My Bondage and My Freedom]] |year=1855}}</ref> describe the "self-made man in similar language: "Being possessionless and unencumbered by authority is the necessary beginning state for the potential self-made man. One cannot be “made” by the help of a father, teacher, mentor, etc.…, but must rise by one’s own grit, determination, discipline, and opportunism. The irony is that they have made themselves free from bounds and possessions, in a sense impoverished, so that they can then begin to acquire power and wealth on their own. The key is to acquire those possessions and power without help. The goal, then, is not to become famous or wealthy in the literal sense, but to participate in something precise and mythical."<ref name="Dixon_thesis_2011"/>

[[File:Frederick Douglass, head-and-shoulders portrait, facing right, ca 1850-1860 edit.jpg|left|thumb|Frederick Douglass, photographed between 1850 and 1860.]]Frederick Douglass developed the concepts in a series of lectures "[[Self-Made Men]]" from 1859 onward, for example 1895,<ref name="Douglass_1895_selfmademen">{{cite web |series=The Frederick Douglass Papers at the Library of Congress: Speech, Article, and Book File |title=Self-Made Men: Address before the Students of the Indian Industrial School |quote="Self-made men […] are the men who owe little or nothing to birth, relationship, friendly surroundings; to wealth inherited or to early approved means of education; who are what they are, without the aid of any of the favoring conditions by which other men usually rise in the world and achieve great results."|location=Carlisle, Pennsylvania |agency=Library of Congress |year=1895}}Folder 1 of 16 (Series: Speech, Article, and Book File—B: Frederick Douglass, Undated)</ref>{{rp|549–50}} which were published and archived in "The Frederick Douglass Papers at the Library of Congress". In his 1872 lecture<ref name="Douglass_1872_selfmademen">{{cite web |series=The Frederick Douglass Papers at the Library of Congress: Speech, Article, and Book File |title=Self-Made Men  |publisher=Monadnock |url=http://monadnock.net/douglass/self-made-men.html|year=1872}}</ref> Douglass noted that there were "no such men as self-made men. That term implies an individual independence of the past and present which can never exist...Our best and most valued acquisitions have been obtained either from our contemporaries or from those who have preceded us in the field of thought and discovery. We have all either begged, borrowed or stolen. We have reaped where others have sown, and that which others have strown, we have gathered."<ref name="Douglass_1872_selfmademen"/> However, he then provided one of his most detailed descriptions of the self-made man,<ref name="Douglass_1872_selfmademen"/>

{{quote|Self-made men are the men who, under peculiar difficulties and without the ordinary helps of favoring circumstances, have attained knowledge, usefulness, power and position and have learned from themselves the best uses to which life can be put in this world, and in the exercises of these uses to build up worthy character. They are the men who owe little or nothing to birth, relationship, friendly surroundings; to wealth inherited or to early approved means of education; who are what they are, without the aid of any favoring conditions by which other men usually rise in the world and achieve great results....They are the men who, in a world of schools, academies, colleges and other institutions of learning, are often compelled by unfriendly circumstances to acquire their education elsewhere and, amidst unfavorable conditions, to hew out for themselves a way to success, and thus to become the architects of their own good fortunes....From the depths of poverty such as these have often come. ...From hunger, rags and destitution, they have come..."|Frederick Douglass. 1872. "Self-Made Men" (full-text)}}

==Self-made men==
F. W. Pine wrote in his introduction of the 1916 publication of ''The Autobiography of Benjamin Franklin'', that Franklin's biography provided the "most remarkable of all the remarkable histories of our self-made men" with Franklin as the greatest exemplar of the "self-made man".<ref name="Pine_1916_BFB_HR_GP">{{cite web |url= https://www.gutenberg.org/files/20203/20203-h/20203-h.htm |publisher=Henry Holt and Company via Gutenberg Press |year=1916 |editor-first=Frank Woodworth |editor-last=Pine |number=20203|title=Autobiography of Benjamin Franklin |others=Illustrated by E. Boyd Smith}}</ref>
{{quote|"Franklin is a good type of our American manhood. Although not the wealthiest or the most powerful, he is undoubtedly, in the versatility of his genius and achievements, the greatest of our self-made men. The simple yet graphic story in the Autobiography of his steady rise from humble boyhood in a tallow-chandler shop, by industry, economy, and perseverance in self-improvement, to eminence, is the most remarkable of all the remarkable histories of our self-made men. It is in itself a wonderful illustration of the results possible to be attained in a land of unequaled opportunity by following Franklin's maxims."|Frank Woodworth Pine 1916}}

[[Abraham Lincoln]],<ref name="Blumenthal_2017_Lincoln">{{cite book |title=A Self-Made Man:The Political Life of Abraham Lincoln Volume I, 1809 – 1849 |first=Sidney |last=Blumenthal|publisher=Simon & Schuster |pages=576 |isbn=9781476777269 |date=May 2016 |url=http://www.simonandschuster.com/books/A-Self-Made-Man/Sidney-Blumenthal/The-Political-Life-of-Abraham-Lincoln/9781476777269}}</ref> [[Frederick Douglass]], [[P. T. Barnum]], [[Booker T. Washington]], and [[Andrew Carnegie]] have also been described as self-made men.<ref name="Dixon_thesis_2011">{{cite thesis |url=https://ir.ua.edu/bitstream/handle/123456789/1027/file_1.pdf |format=PDF |title=All about the Benjamins: the Nineteenth Century Character Assassination of Benjamin Franklin |first=Charles Robert |last=Dixon |publisher=[[The University of Alabama]] |location=[[Tuscaloosa]], [[Alabama]] |year=2011 |pages=222}}</ref>{{rp|8}} Both Carnegie and [[Lee Iacocca]] acknowledge that their own autobiographies were influenced by Franklin's.<ref name="Dixon_thesis_2011"/>{{rp|8}} In theirs, both [[Abraham Lincoln]] and [[Ronald Reagan]] described their own origins as somewhat disadvantaged to reflect the narrative of self-made men.<ref name="Dixon_thesis_2011"/>{{rp|8}} Blumenthal began his 2016 biography of Lincoln—''A Self-Made Man''—with the phrase, "I used to be a slave", referring to Lincoln's claim in 1856 that his "domineering and uneducated father" "exploited" young Lincoln by "renting" him out to "rural neighbors in Indiana." Following his escape from servitude, Lincoln re-invented himself.<ref name="NYT_Blumenthal_2017_Lincoln">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/05/15/books/review/a-self-made-man-the-political-life-of-abraham-lincoln-1809-1849-by-sidney-blumenthal.html |title=‘A Self-Made Man: The Political Life of Abraham Lincoln, 1809–1849,’ by Sidney Blumenthal |first=Steven |last=Hahn |date=May 13, 2016 |access-date=November 13, 2017}}</ref> Lincoln was inspired by Franklin's ''Autobiography''.<ref name="Donald_Lincoln_1995">{{cite book |title=Lincoln |first=David Herbert |last=Donald |isbn=1439126283 |publisher=Simon & Schuster |url=https://books.google.ca/books?isbn=1439126283 |date=2016 |orig-year=1995}}</ref>{{rp|29–31, 38–43}}

In an 1893 article in a railway magazine, Eugene V. Debs offered [[Andrew Johnson]] (1808{{spaced ndash}}1875), the [[List of Presidents of the United States|17th President of the United States]], [[Henry Wilson]] (1812–1875) was the [[List of Vice Presidents of the United States|18th Vice President of the United States]] (1873–75), [[Daniel Webster]](1782{{spaced ndash}}1852) who served twice as [[United States Secretary of State]], [[Edward Everett]], and [[Rufus Choate]] as exemplary nineteenth-century self-made men. Debs contrasted the successful self-made men to those whose "illiteracy, stupidity, lack of ambition, forever keeps them at the bottom...[who] prefer pool to school, and choose to hammer coal and shovel it into a fire-box rather than employ their leisure in learning what they must know if they expect to rise." He calls on them to "resolve upon a change of habits — renounce follies and vices, obtain elementary books and study."<ref name="Debs_smm">{{cite news |title=Self-Made Men |first=Eugene V. |last=Debs |series=Unsigned editorial |magazine=Brotherhood of Locomotive Firemen and Enginemen's Magazine |volume=17 |number=4 |date=April 1893 |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=BOs0AQAAIAAJ&pg=RA5-PA267&lpg=RA5-PA267&dq=The+term+“self-made+men”+is+seemingly+paradoxical |quote="The term “self-made men” is seemingly paradoxical — since men who rise from obscurity to eminence in any of the walks of life, must have been assisted by agencies quite independent of themselves " |access-date=November 14, 2017 }}</ref>{{rp|267–217}}

In John G. Cawelti's 1965 book entitled ''Apostles of the self-made man'', he listed Benjamin Franklin, [[Thomas Jefferson]], [[Ralph Waldo Emerson]], Horatio Alger, and [[John Dewey]] as individuals "who either played a major role in shaping the success ideal or were associate with it in the public mind."<ref name="Salzman">{{cite book |title=American Studies: An Annotated Bibliography |volume=2 |editor-first=Jack |editor-last=Salzman|quote=Cawelti focused on "different definitions of success", "how interpretations of the self-made man changed". He used 3 main sources for the self-improvement theme: 1) individual figures: "Thomas Jefferson, Ralph Waldo Emerson, Horatio Alger, John Dewey, who either played a major role in shaping the success ideal or were associate with it in the public mind", 2) "success manuals" from the "late 18th century to 1900" and 3)"self-made man as central character in fictional narratives." Cawelti explored "the characteristic complex of ideas about the self-made man "that reveal connections between social conditions and the divergent notions of success" from ''American Studies: An Annotated Bibliography'', Volume 2 edited by Jack Salzman}}</ref>{{rp|1209}}<ref name="Cawelti_1965">{{cite book|last=Cawelti|first=John G.|title=Apostles of the self-made man|year=1988|publisher=University of Chicago Press|location=Chicago|isbn=9780226098708|edition= |orig-year=1965 |pages=279 }}</ref>

Frank Giuffrida's parents were [[Sicily|Sicilian]] immigrants who lived in Lawrence, Massachusetts. He began to work before he completed high school to run the family butcher shop when his father died. He opened the Hilltop Steakhouse after he sold the family store. His innovative strategy was to offer large size portions in a large scale restaurant spaces, making up for the extra cost of generous portions by the [[Economies of scale|economy of scale]].<ref name="Slate_2014"/> According to the ''New York Times'', the "Hilltop exceeded $27 million gross" in 1987.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/04/06/garden/oh-to-dine-in-saugus-mass.html |title=Oh, to Dine in Saugus, Mass. |first=Bryan |last=Miller |date=April 6, 1988 |access-date=November 12, 2017}}</ref>

In the field of modern art, [[Arshile Gorky]] has been described as a self-made man who rose from "a dark, rich peasant culture" to prominence among "New York modern artists" through his "self-taught erudition and aggressive principles."<ref name="newyorker_2003">{{cite news |url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2003/09/08/self-made-man |date=2003 |work=The New Yorker |title=Self-Made Man: How Arshile Gorky changed art |first=Peter |last= Schjeldahl |access-date=November 12, 2017}}</ref> In the restaurant business Frank Giuffrida, the owner and manager of the [[Hilltop Steakhouse]] which opened in [[Saugus]] 1961 and became the biggest restaurant in the United States by the 1980s, is described as self-made man in the ''Slate'' article.<ref name="Slate_2014"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/1987/08/31/how-hilltop-became-biggest-restaurant/45smjbLsgjPMcJONRjQeQN/story.html |title=How the Hilltop became the biggest restaurant in the US 
|work=Boston Globe |date=September 4, 1987 |first=Charles |last=Stein}}</ref>

==In literature and popular culture==
===Ragged Dick (1868)===
{{main|Ragged Dick}}

[[Horatio Alger Jr.]]'s six-volume Ragged Dick Series which began with the first full-length novel, ''[[Ragged Dick]]'' published in May 1868, a ''[[Bildungsroman]]'' "whose name became synonymous with the [[rags-to-riches]] narrative", where young Dick eventually became the successful and distinguished Richard Hunter.<ref name="Slate_2014"/><ref>{{Cite book |author=Alger, Horatio Jr. |orig-year=1868|year=2008 |title=[[Ragged Dick]] |editor=Hildegard Hoeller |publisher=[[W. W. Norton & Company]] |series=[[Norton Critical Editions]] |isbn=978-0-393-92589-0}}</ref><ref name="Nackenoff_1997">{{cite book |last=Nackenoff |first=Carol |chapter=The Horatio Alger Myth |title=Myth America: A Historical Anthology |volume=2 |year=1997 |editor-last1=Gerster |editor-first1=Patrick |editor-last2=Cords |editor-first2=Nicholas |publisher=Brandywine Press |location=St. James, NY |isbn=1-881089-97-5}}</ref><ref name="Scharnhorst_1981">{{Cite book |last1=Scharnhorst |first1=Gary |last2=Bales |first2=Jack |year=1981 |title=Horatio Alger Jr.: An Annotated Bibliography of Comment and Criticism |publisher=Scarecrow Press |isbn=978-0-8108-1387-8}}</ref><ref name="Slate_2014"/>

===The Great Gatsby (1925)===
{{main|The Great Gatsby}}

In [[F. Scott Fitzgerald]]'s [[Masterpiece|magnum opus]] [[The Great Gatsby]], describes the downfall of the "archetypal, if somewhat misguided"<ref name="Decker_1994">{{cite journal |series=Novel: A Forum on Fiction |volume=28 |number=1 |date=1994 |title=Gatsby's Pristine Dream: The Diminishment of the Self-Made Man in the Tribal Twenties |first=Jeffrey Louis |last=Decker |pages=52–71 |publisher=Duke University Press |doi=10.2307/1345913 |jstor=1345913 }}</ref> "socially ambitious self-made man" [[Jay Gatsby]] who rose from "an obscure and impoverished Midwestern childhood to become a wealthy and sought-after center of Long Island society".<ref name="120_banned_books">{{cite book |last1=Karolides |first1=Nicholas J. |last2=Bald |first2=Margaret |last3=Sova |first3=Dawn B. |title=120 Banned Books: Censorship Histories of World Literature |edition=Second |year=2011 |publisher=Checkmark Books |isbn=978-0-8160-8232-2 |page=499 |url=https://archive.org/stream/120BannedBooks/120BannedBooks_djvu.txt}}</ref> Gatsby contrasts with Ben Franklin and the characters in Horatio Alger Jr. novels, as successful self-made men. His story serves as a cautionary tale regarding the [[American Dream]] where "an unhappy fate is inevitable for the poor and striving individual, and the rich are allowed to continue without penalty their careless treatment of others' lives."<ref name="120_banned_books"/><ref>{{cite web |last=Hoover |first=Bob |title='The Great Gatsby' still challenges myth of American Dream |date=10 May 2013 |url=http://www.post-gazette.com/stories/ae/movies/great-gatsby-still-challenges-myth-of-american-dream-687050/ |work=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]] |accessdate=10 May 2013}}</ref>

==Ultra high-net-worth individuals==
{{main|Ultra high-net-worth individual}}

According to the 2017 "World Ultra Wealth Report" by research company Wealth-X, "wealth creation" from 1997 through 2017 has been "driven largely by self-made individuals", mainly men.<ref name="wealthx_2017_report">{{cite news |url=https://www.wealthx.com/report/exclusive-uhnwi-analysis-the-world-ultra-wealth-report-2017/ |publisher=Wealth-X |series=World Ultra Wealth Report |title=The World Ultra Wealth Report 2017 |edition=5 |date=June 27, 2017 |access-date=November 12, 2017}}</ref>{{rp|27}} According to the report, ultra high-net-worth individuals (UHNWI), those who have a [[net worth]] of at least [[US$]]30 million, were "predominantly self-made" having "earned their fortunes". Two-thirds of the UHNWI sourced "their wealth from their own efforts" such as "fruitful business ventures or successful investments."<ref name="wealthx_2017_report"/>{{rp|29}} Of the 226,450 UHNWIs, 66% were self-made; of the 7,200 UHNW millennials (born between 1980–1995), 66% were self-made; of the 28,985 UHNW women, 45% were self-made; of the 33,290 UHNWI from emerging Asia (excluding Japan, Singapore and Hong Kong), 68% were self-made; and of the 34,961 UHNW Ivy League individuals, 75% were self-made.<ref name="wealthx_2017_report"/>{{rp|33}}

==Cultural history==
In his 2000 book ''Creating the Modern Man'', cultural historian Tom Pendergast traced the way in which the concept of the self-made man was referenced in men's magazines from 1900 through 1950.<ref name="Pendergast_2000">{{cite book|last=Pendergast|first=Tom|title=Creating the Modern Man: American Magazines and Consumer Culture, 1900–1950|year=2000|publisher=University of Missouri Press|location=Columbia, Missouri and London, UK|isbn=9780826212801|pages=289|edition= |url=https://books.google.ca/books?redir_esc=y&id=FWdKPEtBAHcC&q=self-made+man#v=snippet&q=self-made%20man&f=false}}</ref>{{rp|10}} Pendergast divided masculinity into only two periods: Victorian, which was "based on property-ownership and family", and "post-Victorian", which was "based on a cult of personality, self-improvement, and narcissism".<ref name="Corrales_Pendergast_2003">{{cite journal |title=Corrales on Pendergast, 'Creating the Modern Man: American Magazines and Consumer Culture, 1900-1950' |first=Barbara Smith |last=Corrales |journal=Journal of History|date=January 2003 |access-date=November 12, 2017 |url=https://networks.h-net.org/node/14542/reviews/14821/corrales-pendergast-creating-modern-man-american-magazines-and-consumer}}</ref> He described the "ideal Victorian man" as a "property owning man of character who believed in honesty, integrity, self-restraint, and duty to God, country, and family".<ref name="Pendergast_2000"/>{{rp|10}} The post-Victorian image of the self-made man was crucial to Pendergast's study. He revealed how through magazines men "were encouraged to form their identities around an ideology of hard work."<ref name="Pendergast_2000"/>{{rp|10}}

In September 2011, [[Elizabeth Warren]] challenged the concept of the self-made man in a video that went viral,<ref name="businessinsider_2011">{{cite news |title=Here's The Viral Video Of Elizabeth Warren Going After GOP On 'Class Warfare' Charge |first=Zeke |last=Miller |date=September 21, 2011 |access-date=November 12, 2017 |url=http://www.businessinsider.com/the-viral-video-of-elizabeth-warren-going-after-gop-on-class-warfare-2011-9 |work=Business Insider}}</ref> garnering over one million views on YouTube:<ref name="Warren_YouTube_2011">{{Cite AV media |title=Elizabeth Warren on Debt Crisis, Fair Taxation |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=htX2usfqMEs |publisher=YouTube |people=Elizabeth Warren |date=September 18, 2011 |access-date=November 12, 2017 |medium=video |time=2:05 minutes}} LiveSmartVideos</ref>

{{quote|"There is nobody in this country who got rich on his own. Nobody...You built a factory out there? Good for you. But I want to be clear: you moved your goods to market on the roads the rest of us paid for; you hired workers the rest of us paid to educate; you were safe in your factory because of police forces and fire forces that the rest of us paid for. You didn’t have to worry that marauding bands would come and seize everything at your factory, and hire someone to protect against this, because of the work the rest of us did....Now look, you built a factory and it turned into something terrific, or a great idea? God bless. Keep a big hunk of it. But part of the underlying social contract is you take a hunk of that and pay forward for the next kid who comes along."|[[Elizabeth Warren]], Massachusetts Senate candidate (2011)}}

